| 2008 || {{dts|May 5}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, Corrections Corporation of America (now CoreCivic) || A ''{{w|New York Times}}'' article talks about deaths in ICE detention centers and the lack of accountability around them. It provides a detailed account of the death in ICE's Elizabeth Detention Center in New Jersey of Boubacar Bah, a 52-year-old tailor from Guinea.<ref name=nytimes-detention-deaths-2008>{{cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/05/nyregion/05detain.html|title = Few Details on Immigrants Who Died in Custody|last = Bernstein|first = Nina|date = May 5, 2008|accessdate = July 26, 2021|publisher = New York Times}}</ref> || New Jersey || Elizabeth Detention Center, Elizabeth
|-
| 2008 || {{dts|May 11}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE || Two articles in the ''{{w|Washington Post}}'', published on the same day, look at cases of deaths in ICE detention. One is about Yusif Osman, a U.S. legal resident from Ghana detained on smuggling charges.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/specials/immigration/cwc_d1p1.html|title = System of Neglect: As Tighter Immigration Policies Strain Federal Agencies, The Detainees in Their Care Often Pay a Heavy Cost|last = Priest|first = Dana|last2 = Goldstein|first2 = Amy|date = May 11, 2008|accessdate = July 26, 2021|publisher = Washington Post}}</ref> Another is about Francisco Castaneda from El Salvador, detained after drug possession charges.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/nation/specials/immigration/cwc_d1sidebar.html|title = E-Mails Show Attempt To 'Patch Up' a Case Of Medical Negligence|last = Priest|first = Dana|last2 = Goldstein|first2 = Amy|date = May 11, 2008|accessdate = July 26, 2021|publisher = Washington Post}}</ref> Both had died at the Otay Mesa detention center in the San Diego region. || California || Otay Mesa detention center, San Diego
|-
| 2008 || {{dts|June 4}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GAO || A report by the Government Accountability Office (GAO) covering 23 detention centers shows 3 of the centers to be in noncompliance with ICE's medical care standards at the time. It also finds 4 of the 23 centers to be in noncompliance with ICE's detainee grievance standards.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-08-869t|title = Alien Detention Standards: Observations on the Adherence to ICE's Medical Standards in Detention Facilities|date = June 4, 2008|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref>
|-
| 2008 || {{dts|October}} || Detention center || Criticism/challenge || ICE, New York City Bar Association || The {{w|New York City Bar Association}} receives a petition signed by 100 men in the Varick Street Federal Detention Facility in Manhattan, New York, describing "cramped, filthy quarters where dire medical needs were ignored and hungry prisoners were put to work for $1 a day" according to a ''New York Times'' article published in November 2009.<ref name=nytimes-varick/> || New York || Varick Street Federal Detention Facility, Manhattan, New York City
|-
| 2009 || around March || Detention center || Start || ICE, Immigration Centers of America || A detention center is opened in [[w:Farmville, Virginia|Farmville]], {{w|Virginia}}, through an agreement with the city of Farmville, amidst protests. The center is operated by Immigration Centers of America.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://richmond.com/news/protest-against-immigrant-detention-center-draws-in-farmville/article_ec069725-4e50-5f2e-b7bd-d964918fad35.html|title = Protest against immigrant detention center draws 150 in Farmville|publisher = Richmond Times-Dispatch|date = March 8, 2009|accessdate = July 26, 2021|last = Ruff|first = Jamie}}</ref> The National Immigrant Justice Center woud later list this as an example of "middleman contracting" considered improper under federal procurement law.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://immigrantjustice.org/research-items/policy-brief-dark-money-trail-behind-private-detention-immigration-centers-america|title = Policy Brief: The Dark Money Trail Behind Private Detention: Immigration Centers Of America-Farmville|date = October 7, 2019|accessdate = July 26, 2021|publisher = National Immigrant Justice Center}}</ref>
|-
| 2009 || {{dts|October 28}} || Detention capacity || Update || ICE || The DHS Appropriations Act of 2009, for the first time, imposes a "bed mandate" on ICE based on language suggested by Senator {{w|Robert Byrd}}. Specifically, it says: "That funding made available under this heading shall maintain a level of not less than 33,400 detention beds through September 30, 2010."<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/PLAW-111publ83/pdf/PLAW-111publ83.pdf|title = Department of Homeland Security Appropriations Act, 2010|date = October 28, 2009|accessdate = April 30, 2021}}</ref><ref name=wp-bed-quota-fact-check>{{cite web|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2015/05/15/clintons-inaccurate-claim-that-immigrant-detention-facilities-have-a-legal-requirement-to-fill-beds/|title = Clinton’s inaccurate claim that immigrant detention facilities have a legal requirement to fill beds|last = Lee|first = Michelle|date = May 15, 2015|accessdate = April 30, 2021|publisher = Washington Post}}</ref> The capacity would drop to 32,800 in Fiscal Year 2012 and increase to 34,000 in Fiscal Year 2015, and fluctuate further in the coming years.<ref name=bed-quota-timeline/> There would later be comments by politicians claiming that the mandate requires ICE to ''fill'' the capacity every day, but fact-checking by the {{w|Washington Post}}<ref name=wp-bed-quota-fact-check/> and {{w|PolitiFact}}<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2018/jul/06/alexandria-ocasio-cortez/alexandria-ocasio-cortez-misrepresents-ices-detent/|title = ICE is required to fill 34,000 beds with detainees every single night and that number has only been increasing since 2009.|last = Geng|first = Lucia|date = July 6, 2018|accessdate = April 30, 2021|publisher = PolitiFact}}</ref> would reject that inference.
