| 2010 || {{dts|February}} (approx) || Detention center || End || ICE || ICE announces its plans to close the Varick Street Federal Detention Facility in Manhattan, New York and relocate those currently held in it to prisons in New Jersey; Varick Street would only be used as a temporary holding location for a maximum of 12 hours per person. However, plans to close the place run into trouble due to challenges relocating people with medical and mental health challenges.<ref name=nytimes-varick-2>{{cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/24/nyregion/24varick.html|title = Illness Hinders Plans to Close Immigration Jail|last = Bernstein|first = Nina|date = February 23, 2010|accessdate = April 29, 2021|publisher = New York Times}}</ref> While there are some positive reactions, advocates push for deeper structural changes whereby people would be detained less; concerns are also raised about how relocating detainees would deprive them of their existing relationships with counsel based in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aclu.org/other/statement-us-department-homeland-security-regarding-detainees-varick-federal-detention|title = Statement to the U.S. Department of Homeland Security Regarding Detainees at Varick Federal Detention Facility|date = February 1, 2010|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.colorlines.com/articles/varick-closing-thats-not-answer-our-broken-detention-system|title = Varick Is Closing, But That's Not The Answer to Our Broken Detention System. The Varick Federal Detention Facility is days away from closure, and this should be good news.|last = Hing|first = Julianne|publisher = ColorLines|date = February 25, 2010|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www2.nycbar.org/htmlemail/44thST/44sn/march-2010-pro-bono-varick.html|title = Varick Street Detention Facility to Close by End of February|date = March 1, 2010|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref> || New York || Varick Street Federal Detention Facility, Manhattan, New York City
