| 2011 || || Detention standards || Update || ICE || ICE releases an updated version of its Performance-Based National Detention Standards (PBNDS) for its detention centers. ICE states that "PBNDS 2011 is crafted to improve medical and mental health services, increase access to legal services and religious opportunities, improve communication with detainees with limited English proficiency, improve the process for reporting and responding to complaints, and increase recreation and visitation."<ref name=pbnds-2011>{{cite web|url = https://www.ice.gov/detain/detention-management/2011|title = 2011 Operations Manual ICE Performance-Based National Detention Standards|accessdate = April 29, 2021|publisher = U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement}}</ref><ref name=ice-detention-standards/>
|-
| 2011 || {{dts|August}} || Detention center || Start || ICE, GEO Group || The East Wing of the {{w|Adelanto Detention Center}}, a detention facility managed by {{w|GEO Group}} for ICE, opens for operation. The facility had previously been a state prison for adult male inmates before the GEO Group purchased it in 2010 and contracted with ICE in May 2011 to use it for immigration detention. The West Wing would open in July 2012. || California || Adelanto Detention Center, Adelanto, San Bernandino County
|-
| 2012 || {{dts|March 13}} || Detention center || Start || ICE, GEO Group || The Karnes County Civil Detention Center is opened by ICE, described as its first "designed-and-built civil detention center" and intended for low-risk, minimum-security adult male detainees. The 608-bed center is designed and is to be operated by GEO group. The agreement with Karnes County for the center had been entered into in December 2010. This is the first of several planned detention center creations and upgrades to make them feel less like prison. Immigrant rights groups have mixed reactions, with some seeing it as a step forward, and others expressing concerns about private operation of the prison as well as the continued use of detention centers instead of switching more completely to monitoring technology such as ankle bracelets.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/ice-opens-its-first-ever-designed-and-built-civil-detention-center|title = ICE opens its first-ever designed-and-built civil detention center. New facility in Texas opens today for low-risk, minimum security adult male detainees|date = March 13, 2012|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.npr.org/2012/03/14/148538183/ice-opens-immigrant-detention-center-in-rural-texas|title = Trying To Make Immigrant Detention Less Like Prison|last = Sullivan|first = Laura|date = March 14, 2012|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = NPR}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/14/us/model-immigration-detention-center-unveiled-in-texas.html|title = Detention for Immigrants That Looks Less Like Prison|date = March 13, 2012|accessdate = July 4, 2021|last = Semple|first = Kirk|last2 = Eaton|first2 = Tim|publisher = New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.oklahoman.com/article/3658707/feds-unveil-reform-minded-immigration-site|title = Feds unveil reform-minded immigration site|last = Weissert|date = March 18, 2012|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = The Oklahoman}}</ref> || Texas || Karnes County Civil Detention Center, Karnes City, Karnes County
|-
| 2012 || || || Start || CIVIC (now Freedom for Immigrants) || Freedom for Immigrants is founded by Christina Fialho and Christina Mansfield as Community Initiatives for Visiting Immigrants in Confinement (CIVIC).<ref name=ffi-founding>{{cite web|url = https://www.freedomforimmigrants.org/our-founding|title = Who We Are|publisher = Freedom for Immigrants|accessdate = July 27, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2013 || {{dts|February 22}} || Detention center || Start || CBP (Border Patrol) || {{w|Clint Border Patrol Station}} opens as a migrant detention facility four miles north of the Mexico-U.S. border in {{w|Clint, Texas}}. The 51,000 sq. ft. facility replaces the 22,800 sq. ft. Fabens Border Patrol facility created in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.spa.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Stories/Article/478997/district-participates-in-new-border-patrol-stations-opening-in-clint-texas/|title = District Participates in New Border Patrol Station's Opening in Clint, Texas.|last = Schelby|first = Ronnie|date = March 7, 2013|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref> Clint would be called "the public face of the chaos on America’s southern border" in a 2019 ''New York Times'' piece.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/07/06/us/migrants-border-patrol-clint.html|title=Hungry, Scared and Sick: Inside the Migrant Detention Center in Clint, Tex.|last1=Romero|first1=Simon|date=2019-07-06|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2019-07-06|last2=Kanno-Youngs|first2=Zolan|issn=0362-4331|last3=Fernandez|first3=Manny|last4=Borunda|first4=Daniel|last5=Montes|first5=Aaron|last6=Dickerson|first6=Caitlin}}</ref> || Texas || Client Border Patrol Station, Clint
|-
| 2013 || {{dts|November 20}} (first report), December 6 (reissue) || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GAO || The U.S. Government Accountability Office publishes a report on ICE's handling of sexual abuse risks in its detention centers, and makes several recommendations. The context is to gauge ICE's compliance with the {{w|Prison Rape Elimination Act}}.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-14-38|title = Immigration Detention:Additional Actions Could Strengthen DHS Efforts to Address Sexual Abuse (Reissued on December 6, 2013)|date = November 20, 2013|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref>
|-
| 2014 || || || || Queer Detainee Empowerment Project || The Queer Detainee Empowerment Project (QDEP) is founded. Google dates the site to January 2014; the first Wayback Machine snapshot is from March 2014.
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|January 29}} || Detention standards || || ICE || The National Immigrant Justice Center conducts depositions of the chief of ICE's Detention Monitoring Unit and a former ICE contracting officer regarding ICE's contracting and inspections processes for immigration detention facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://immigrantjustice.org/depositions-ice-experts|title = Depositions Of ICE Experts|date = January 29, 2014|accessdate = July 26, 2021|publisher = National Immigrant Justice Center}}</ref>
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|June 20}} || Detention center (family detention) || Start || DHS/ICE || DHS announces that it is setting up a temporary facility for detaining adults with children in {{w|expedited removal}} on the {{w|Artesia, New Mexico}} campus of the {{w|Federal Law Enforcement Training Centers}}. This comes amidst a surge in border-crossing, both by unaccompanied minors and by families with children.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dhs.gov/news/2014/06/20/fact-sheet-artesia-temporary-facility-adults-children-expedited-removal|title = Fact Sheet: Artesia Temporary Facility for Adults With Children in Expedited Removal|date = June 20, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021|publisher = U.S. Department of Homeland Security}}</ref> The facility would generate controversy among the residents of Artesia.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.latimes.com/nation/immigration/la-na-ff-artesia-detention-center-20140914-story.html|title = Detention center brings immigration debate to small-town New Mexico|date = September 13, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021|last = Carcamo|first = Cindy|publisher = Los Angeles Times}}</ref> || New Mexico || Artesia
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|June 24}} || Detention capacity || Update || DHS (both ICE and CBP) || DHS Secretary {{w|Jeh Johnson}} submits written testimony to the House Committee on Homeland Security detailing a multi-pronged response to the [[w:2014 American immigration crisis|2014 migrant surge]], particularly the surge in child migrants. Part of the strategy includes increasing detention capacity for children and for families.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dhs.gov/news/2014/06/24/written-testimony-dhs-secretary-jeh-johnson-house-committee-homeland-security|title = Written testimony of DHS Secretary Jeh Johnson for a House Committee on Homeland Security hearing titled “Dangerous Passage: The Growing Problem of Unaccompanied Children Crossing the Border”|publisher = U.S. Department of Homeland Security|date = June 24, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021}}</ref><ref name=hrf-berks>{{cite web|url = https://www.humanrightsfirst.org/sites/default/files/HRF-Family-Det-Penn-rep-final.pdf|title = Family Detention in Berks County, Pennsylvania|date = August 1, 2015|accessdate = July 3, 2021|publisher = Human Rights First}}</ref>
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|July}} || Detention center (child detention) || Start || CBP || The [[w:Ursula (detention center)|Ursula detention center]] (official name "Central Processing Center"), the largest detention center operated by Customs and Border Protection, opens for operation in {{w|McAllen, Texas}} at the site of a former Gmark warehouse, and extending the existing McAllen border station.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.valleycentral.com/news/local-news/new-mcallen-facility-to-house-1000-immigrant-children/|title = New McAllen facility to house 1,000 immigrant children|date = July 1, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021|last = Crandall|first = Brett|publisher = ValleyCentral}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.cnn.com/2014/06/24/us/texas-warehouse-unaccompanied-minors/index.html|title = Converted warehouse to process unaccompanied child migrants in Texas|last = Cuevas|first = Mayra|last2 = Ellis|first2 = Ralph|date = June 25, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021|publisher = CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-08-04/conditions-migrants-detention-center-texas-are-bleak-and-overcrowded-sometimes|title = Conditions for migrants at a detention center in Texas are bleak and overcrowded|last = Margolis|first = Jason|date = August 4, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021|publisher = TheWorld}}</ref> In June 2018, it would gain notoriety for the practice of keeping children in large cages made of {{w|chain-link fencing}}.<ref name=Frej>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/images-inside-center-immigrants_us_5b27bebae4b0f9178a9f6f7f|title=These Are The Texas Immigration Center Photos Stirring Anti-Trump Outrage|last=Frej|first=Willa|date=2018-06-18|work=Huffington Post|access-date=2018-06-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618224954/https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/images-inside-center-immigrants_us_5b27bebae4b0f9178a9f6f7f|archive-date=18 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> || Texas || Central Processing Center (aka Ursula Detention Center), McAllen
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|August}} || Detention center (family detention) || Repurposing || ICE || The Karnes Family Residential Center is opened in Karnes County for family detention. The original detention center opened in Karnes in 2012 had been a low-security facility for adult males.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.texastribune.org/2016/12/06/immigration-detention-centers-will-continue-operat/|title = Immigration detention centers will continue operating despite judge's ruling. Two immigration detention centers in Texas will continue their day-to-day operations despite a Travis County judge’s ruling last week that denied the facilities state licenses.| last = Aguilar|first = Julián|publisher = Texas Tribune|date = December 6, 2016|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref> || Texas || Karnes Family Residential Center, Karnes City, Karnes County
|-
| 2014  || {{dts|August 22}} || Court case || Criticism/challenge || ICE || The lawsuit ''M.S.P.C. v. Johnson'' is filed against DHS/ICE for the conditions in the detention center at Artesia, New Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.bostonreview.net/us/lauren-carasik-artesia-fletc-immigrant|title = The American “Deportation Mill”. Immigrant families detained in Artesia, New Mexico, are suing the U.S. government|last = Carasik|first = Lauren|date = September 9, 2014|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Boston Review}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aclu.org/press-releases/groups-sue-us-government-over-life-threatening-deportation-process-against-mothers|title = Groups sue U.S. government over life-threatening deportation process against mothers and children escaping extreme violence in Central America|date = August 22, 2014|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = American Civil Liberties Union}}</ref> Followup investigations by ICE in response to the lawsuit would ultimately lead to an announcement of the closure of the detention center.<ref name=sunlight>{{cite journal|url = https://open.mitchellhamline.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1133&context=mhlr|title = Sunlight is the Best Disinfectant: The Role of the Media in Shaping Immigration Policy|author = Ana Pottratz Acosta|journal = Mitchell Hamline Law Review|volume = 44|issue = 3}}</ref> || New Mexico || Artesia
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|October 10}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GAO || A U.S. Government Accountability Office report on ICE detention standards and costs finds that ICE uses two methods to collect detention center cost data, and also that it has three sets of detention standards (2000 NDS, 2008 PBNDS, 2011 PBNDS) with each set of standards followed by at least some detention centers.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-15-153|title = Immigration Detention: Additional Actions Needed to Strengthen Management and Oversight of Facility Costs and Standards|date = October 10, 2014|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref><ref name=americanprogress/>
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|November 18}} (announcement), December (execution) || Detention center (family detention) || End || DHS/ICE || DHS announces that the temporary family detention facility in Artesia, New Mexico will be shut down by the end of December. The detention center in Dilley, South Texas that is planned for a December opening is expected to make up the lost detention capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.abqjournal.com/497946/feds-to-ship-immigrants-out-of-artesia-in-December.html|title = Detention center in Artesia to close|last = Coleman|first = Michael|date = November 18, 2014|accessdate = July 3, 2021|publisher = Albuquerque Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.santafenewmexican.com/news/u-s-to-close-immigrant-detention-center-in-artesia/article_056a06ab-6044-5f04-950f-822b22779462.html|title = U.S. to close immigrant detention center in Artesia|last = Caldwell|first = Alicia|date = November 18, 2014|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Santa Fe New Mexican}}</ref><ref name=sunlight/> || New Mexico || Artesia
|-
| 2014 || {{dts|December 15}} || Detention center (family detention) || Start || ICE, Corrections Corporation of America (now CoreCivic) || The {{w|South Texas Family Residential Center}} opens in Dilley, South Texas. It has a capacity of 2,400 and is intended to detain mainly women and children from Central America. It is managed by the [[w:CoreCivic|Corrections Corporation of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/16/us/homeland-security-chief-opens-largest-immigration-detention-center-in-us.html|title = Detention Center Presented as Deterrent to Border Crossings|last = Preston|first = Julia|date = December 15, 2014|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/south-texas-immigration-detention-center-set-to-open/|title=South Texas immigration detention center set to open|date=15 December 2014|publisher=|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref> A ''{{w|Washington Post}}'' article in August 2016 would describe the setup of the center as based on a 4-year, $1 billion, no-bid contract, that circumvented the contract bidding process by using the city of Eloy, Arizona as a middleman.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/inside-the-administrations-1-billion-deal-to-detain-central-american-asylum-seekers/2016/08/14/e47f1960-5819-11e6-9aee-8075993d73a2_story.html|title = Inside the administration’s $1 billion deal to detain Central American asylum seekers|last = Harlan|first = Chico|date = August 14, 2016|accessdate = July 27, 2021|publisher = Washington Post}}</ref> || Texas || South Texas Family Residential Center, Dilley
|-
| 2014 {{snd}} 2015 || {{dts|December 16, 2014}} {{snd}} August 6, 2015; ICE policy change May 2015 || Court case || Criticism/challenge || ICE || The court case ''RILR v. Johnson'' is processed by the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia. The plaintiffs are three mothers who came with their children, have asylum claims, and were locked up. The claim is that ICE has been locking up families -- including those with legitimate asylum claims -- as a way of deterring potential border-crossers, and that the "no-release" policy for detainees is a violation of federal immigration law and regulations, as well as the Fifth Amendment of the U.S. Constitution. In May 2015, ICE announces that it will no longer consider general deterrence in detention decisions for families, upon which all parties agree to administratively close the case, with the possibility of reopening if ICE changes its policy.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aclu.org/cases/rilr-v-johnson|title = RILR V. JOHNSON|publisher = American Civil Liberties Union|accessdate = July 3, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://bostonreview.net/blog/louis-fisher-immigration-ICE-asylum|title = A Tale of Two Immigration Judgments|date = March 31, 2015|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Boston Review}}</ref>
|-
| 2015 || {{dts|May 13}} || Detention standards, detention policy || Update || ICE || ICE announces a number of changes to its standards and practices around detention. One of the changes is to stop invoking deterrence effects as a factor in custody determinations for all families; this happens in the context of the ''RILR v. Johnson'' case that is seeking something similar. The creation of an Advisory Committee on Family Residential Centers, consistent with the {{w|Federal Advisory Committee Act}}, is also announced. Other efforts to improve and monitor family detention practices are also announced.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.ice.gov/news/releases/ice-announces-enhanced-oversight-family-residential-centers|title = ICE announces enhanced oversight for family residential centers|date = May 13, 2015|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dhs.gov/news/2015/06/24/statement-secretary-jeh-c-johnson-family-residential-centers|title = Statement By Secretary Jeh C. Johnson On Family Residential Centers|date = June 24, 2015|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Department of Homeland Security}}</ref>
|-
| 2015 || {{dts|September 17}} || Detention standards (family detention) || Criticism/challenge || ICE, CBP, U.S. Commission on Civil Rights || A report by the {{w|United States Commission on Civil Rights}} titled "With Liberty and Justice for All: The State of Civil Rights at Immigration Detention Facilities" recommends an end to the practice of family detention, based on conditions in detention centers, violation of the Flores settlement conditions, and the lack of due process for detainees. The report is based on hearings in May and visits to the Karnes detention center and a processing center in Port Isabel.<ref name=usccr-2015>{{cite web|url = https://www.usccr.gov/pubs/docs/Statutory_Enforcement_Report2015.pdf|title = With Liberty and Justice for All: The State of Civil Rights at Immigration Detention Facilities|date = September 17, 2015|accessdate = July 27, 2021|publisher = United States Commission on Civil Rights}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-immigrant-detention-centers-civil-rights-20150917-story.html|title = Detention conditions ‘similar, if not worse’ than migrants’ home countries, report says|last = Muskal|first = Michael|date = September 18, 2015|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref name=americanprogress>{{cite web|url = https://www.americanprogress.org/issues/immigration/reports/2015/12/18/127769/how-for-profit-companies-are-driving-immigration-detention-policies/|title = How For-Profit Companies Are Driving Immigration Detention Policies|last = Gruberg|first = Sharita|date = December 18, 2015|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Center for American Progress}}</ref> || Texas || Karnes Family Residential Center, Karnes City, Karnes County; Port Isabel
|-
| 2015 || {{dts|October 22}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE || The report "Lives In Peril: How Ineffective Inspections Make ICE Complicit In Detention Center Abuse" is published by the National Immigrant Justice Center and Detention Watch Network as part of The Immigration Detention Transparency And Human Rights Project. It is based on information collected through {{w|Freedom of Information Act}} requests filed by NIJC and a federal court order following three years of litigation.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://immigrantjustice.org/lives-peril-how-ineffective-inspections-make-ice-complicit-detention-center-abuse|title = Lives In Peril: How Ineffective Inspections Make ICE Complicit In Detention Center Abuse|date = October 22, 2015|accessdate = July 26, 2021|publisher = National Immigrant Justice Center}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || || Detention standards || Update || ICE || ICE revises its 2011 Performance-Based National Detention Standards (PBNDS) to "ensure consistency with federal legal and regulatory requirements as well as prior ICE policies and policy statements." The revision is reflected through updates in the 2011 PBNDS on the ICE website, rather than a separate set of standards.<ref name=pbnds-2011/>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|January 21}} (announcement), {{dts|January 27}} (official notice) || Detention center (child detention) || Criticism/challenge || ICE, Pennsylvania Department of Human Services (PA DHS) || The Pennsylvania Department of Human Services (PA DHS) issues notice that the licensing of the Berks County Residential Center to operate as a child detention facility is being revoked and will not be renewed.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://services.dpw.state.pa.us/Resources/Documents/Pdf/ViolationReports/20160128_14386.pdf|title = The Department of Human Services is not renewing the certificate of compliance issued to the Berks County Commissioners to operate the Berks County Residential Center as a child residential facility|date = January 27, 2016|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Pennsylvania Department of Human Services}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www2.law.temple.edu/csj/publication/pennsylvanias-legal-authority-shut-berks-family-detention-center/|title = Pennsylvania’s legal authority to shut down Berks Family Detention Center|date = October 31, 2017|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Center for Social Justice, Temple University Beasley School of Law}}</ref> The decision would be appealed in February;<ref>{{cite web|url = http://services.dpw.state.pa.us/Resources/Documents/Pdf/ViolationReports/20160211_14386.pdf|title = This is to acknowledge receipt of your request to appeal the Department's decision to NON-RENEW and REVOKE the license for Berks County Residential Center.|date = February 8, 2016|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Pennsylvania Department of Human Services}}</ref> PA DHS would issue reports of violations to the Berks County Residential Center in the years from 2016 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://services.dpw.state.pa.us/dhs/ViolationReport.aspx?reportid=14386&fac=BERKS%20COUNTY%20RESIDENTIAL%20CENTER#.WywNLlOUuRu|title = Inspection/Violation Reports for BERKS COUNTY RESIDENTIAL CENTER|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Pennsylvania Department of Human Services}}</ref> || Pennsylvania || Berks County Residential Center, Leesport, Berks County
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|February 29}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GAO || A U.S. Government Accountability Office report reviews the current state of medical care at ICE's detention centers and makes recommendations that DHS accepts and plans to implement.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-16-231|title = Immigration Detention: Additional Actions Needed to Strengthen Management and Oversight of Detainee Medical Care|date = February 29, 2016|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|March 15}} || Detention standards (monitoring) || Start || ICE, CBP, DHS OIG || The DHS Office of Inspector General (OIG) releases a statement that it will conduct periodic unannounced inspections of CBP and ICE detention centers. This is in response to concerns raised by immigrant rights groups and complaints to the DHS OIG hotline about conditions in detentioon centers. The first inspection is done on the day of this statement.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.oig.dhs.gov/assets/pr/2016/oigpr-031516b.pdf|title = DHS OIG To Periodically Inspect CBP and ICE Detention Facilities|publisher = DHS Office of Inspector General|date = March 15, 2016|accessdate = July 26, 2021}}</ref><ref name=code-red>{{cite web|url = https://immigrantjustice.org/research-items/report-code-red-fatal-consequences-dangerously-substandard-medical-care-immigration|title = Code Red: The Fatal Consequences Of Dangerously Substandard Medical Care In Immigration Detention|date = June 20, 2018|accessdate = July 26, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|October 27}} || Detention center || Start || ICE || ''The Nation'' reports that the {{w|Cibola County Correctional Center}} in [[w:Milan, New Mexico|Milan]], [[w:Cibola County, New Mexico|Cibola County]], {{w|New Mexico}} is reopening as an immigration detention center under contract with ICE, just a month after losing its contract as a minimum-security prison for the {{w|Federal Bureau of Prisons}} and the {{w|United States Marshals Service}}.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/ice-plans-to-reopen-the-very-same-private-prison-the-feds-just-closed/|title = ICE Plans to Reopen the Very Same Private Prison the Feds Just Closed. Advocates cheered when the Justice Department began shuttering its private prisons. But immigration officials saw an opportunity.|author = Seth Freed Wessler|date = October 27, 2016|accessdate = April 30, 2021|publisher = The Nation}}</ref> || New Mexico || Cibola County Correctional Center, Milan, Cibola County
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|October 28}} || Detention contractors || Update || Corrections Corporation of America (now CoreCivic) || Corrections Corporation of America, one of the two major private players in immigration detention (the other being GEO Group) rebrands as CoreCivic.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.corecivic.com/news/corrections-corporation-of-america-rebrands-as-corecivic|title = Corrections Corporation of America Rebrands as CoreCivic|date = October 28, 2016|accessdate = July 27, 2021}}</ref> The renaming happens after years of bad press for the company around its management of detention facilities.
|-
| 2016 || {{dts|November 21}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE || A report by the {{w|Southern Poverty Law Center}} finds that "detainees are routinely denied their due process rights and frequently endure inhumane conditions in isolated facilities that have little oversight from the federal government."<ref name=splc-2016>{{cite web|url = https://www.splcenter.org/20161121/shadow-prisons-immigrant-detention-south|title = Shadow Prisons: Immigrant Detention in the South|date = November 21, 2016|accessdate = April 30, 2021|publisher = Southern Povery Law Center}}</ref>
|-
| 2017 || {{dts|December 11}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, DHS OIG || DHS OIG publishes a report based in unanounced inspections of five detention centers, raising concerns about the treatment and care of ICE detainees at four of the five centers. The report includes one recommendation that ICE accepts and plans to implement.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.oig.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/assets/2017-12/OIG-18-32-Dec17.pdf|title = Concerns about ICE Detainee Treatment and Care at Detention Facilities|date = December 11, 2017|accessdate = July 26, 2021|publisher = DHS Office of Inspector General}}</ref><ref name=code-red/>
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|January}} || Detention center || Criticism/challenge || ICE || The Free Migration Project, National Immigration Project, and Aldea launch a coordinated legal effort to push for a shutdown of the Berks County Residential Center. This follows previous efforts including publications by the Center for Social Justice arguing that Pennsylvania's Department of Human Services has authority to shut down the center based on the revocation of its license.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://freemigrationproject.org/litigation/berks-licensing-lawsuit/|title = Berks Licensing Lawsuit|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = Free Migration Project}}</ref> A coalition of organizations called th Shut Down Berks Coalition is also created to coordinate advocacy work around pushing for a shutdown of the center.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://freemigrationproject.org/shut-down-berks-campaign/|title = Shut Down Berks Campaign|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref> || Pennsylvania || Berks County Residential Center, Leesport, Berks County
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|April 18}} || Detention statistics || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GAO || A U.S. Government Accountability Office report identifies opportunities for ICE to improve its detention cost estimates.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-18-343|title = Immigration Detention: Opportunities Exist to Improve Cost Estimates|date = April 18, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref>
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|May 7}} || Detention policy || Announcement || DHS/ICE, Department of Justice, Department of Health and Human Services || Attorney General Jeff Sessions delivers remarks describing immigration enforcement actions under Donald Trump. Among the "zero tolerance" policies described is what would become known as the {{w|Trump administration family separation policy}}: adults crossing the border with children were being separated from the children with the adults prosecuted by the Department of Justice and the children referred to the Department of Health and Human Services; in many cases the children would also end up detained.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.justice.gov/opa/speech/attorney-general-sessions-delivers-remarks-discussing-immigration-enforcement-actions|title = Attorney General Sessions Delivers Remarks Discussing the Immigration Enforcement Actions of the Trump Administration|date = May 7, 2018|accessdate = October 13, 2021|publisher = U.S. Department of Justice}}</ref><ref name=tafsp>{{cite web|url = https://www.splcenter.org/news/2020/06/17/family-separation-under-trump-administration-timeline|title = Family separation under the Trump administration – a timeline|date = June 17, 2020|accessdate = October 13, 2021|publisher = Southern Poverty Law Center}}</ref> Later commentary would suggest that family separation is partly being used as a way to detain adults who came with children in a way that does not have to comply with the ''Flores'' settlement.<ref name=nyt-flores-kill/>
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|June 14}} || Detention center (temporary shelter) || Start || DHS/ICE || The {{w|Tornillo tent city}} appears to have started operation around this time, as a temporary shelter to detain migrants. It would be shut down in January 2019. || Texas || Tornillo tent city, Tornillo
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|June 20}} || Detentioon policy || Update ||  DHS/ICE, Department of Justice, Department of Health and Human Services, Department of Defense || An executive order signed by then-President {{w|Donald Trump}} changes the administration's [[w:Trump administration family separation policy|policy on family separation]]: adults crossing the border with children would no longer be separated from their children; instead, the entire family would be detained where feasible and not deemed bad for the child's welfare, or the family would not be detained. The longer-term solution is left to Congress. The executive order also directs the Attorney General to seek an update to the ''Flores'' settlement that would allow for more family detention.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/presidential-actions/affording-congress-opportunity-address-family-separation/|title = Affording Congress an Opportunity to Address Family Separation|date = June 20, 2018|accessdate = October 13, 2021|publisher = Trump White House}}</ref><ref name=tafsp/>
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|June 20}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE || A report titled "Code Red: The Fatal Consequences Of Dangerously Substandard Medical Care In Immigration Detention" critically reviews 15 deaths in ICE detention centers covered by the ICE in its detainee death reviews from December 2015 to April 2017. In addition to being highly critical of the poor standard of care, the report is also critical of ICE for its focus on adherence to checklists rather than on qualtiy of care. The report is jointly published by Human Rights Watch, the American Civil Liberties Union, the National Immigrant Justice Center, and Detention Watch Network.<ref name=code-red/>
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|June 26}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, Nakamoto Group, DHS OIG || A report by the DHS Office of the Inspector General finds that neither of ICE's two types of inspection and monitoring processes (Office of Detention Oversight inspections, and inspections contracted out to the Nakamoto Group, a private company) ensure consistent compliance with detention standards, nor do they promote comprehensive deficiency corrections. Five recommendations are made to improve inspections, follow-up, and monitoring of ICE detention facilities, all of which are accepted by ICE with plans to implement.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.oig.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/assets/2018-06/OIG-18-67-Jun18.pdf|title = ICE’s Inspections and Monitoring of Detention Facilities Do Not Lead to Sustained Compliance or Systemic Improvements|date = June 26, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = DHS Office of the Inspector General}}</ref><ref name=npr-nakamoto>{{cite web|url = https://www.npr.org/2019/07/17/741181529/no-meaningful-oversight-ice-contractor-overlooked-problems-at-detention-centers|title = 'No Meaningful Oversight': ICE Contractor Overlooked Problems At Detention Centers|last = Noguchi|first = Yuki|date = July 17, 2019|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = NPR}}</ref>
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|September 27}} || Detention center || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GEO Group, DHS OIG || A report by the DHS Office of the Inspector General identifies several ways that the {{w|Adelanto Detention Center}} fails to meet ICE's Performance-Based National Detention Standards (PBNDS) of 2011. ICE concurs with the recommendations and says it is implementing corrective action.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.oig.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/assets/Mga/2018/oig-18-86-sep18.pdf|title = Management Alert – Issues Requiring Action at the Adelanto ICE Processing Center in Adelanto, California|date = September 27, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = DHS Office of the Inspector General}}</ref><ref name=npr-nakamoto/> || California || Adelanto Detention Center, Adelanto, San Bernandino County
|-
| 2018 || {{dts|November 15}} (query), December 4 (response) || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, Nakamoto Group || A group of United States senators, including {{w|Elizabeth Warren}} (seemingly the leader), {{w|Bernie Sanders}}, and many others, ask Jennifer Nakamoto, the head of the Nakamoto Group, to address concerns about the thoroughness of the Nakamoto Group's inspections raised by recent DHS OIG reports.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.warren.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/2018-11-16%20Letter%20to%20Nakamoto%20Group%20re%20ICE%20Detention%20Facility%20Inspections.pdf|title = Letter to Nakamoto Group re ICE Detention Facility Inspections|last = Warren|first = Elizabeth|date = November 15, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref> Jennifer Nakamoto responds, contesting specific findings in some of the DHS OIG reports, as well as highlighting the limited mandate created by ICE for the Nakamoto Group's inspections, as well as the idea that the Nakamoto Group can only evaluate violations present at the time of the inspections.<ref name=nakamoto-response>{{cite web|url = https://www.warren.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/Attachment%203a%20-%20Response%20Letter%20from%20Nakamoto%20Group.pdf|title = Attachment 3a - Response Letter from Nakamoto Group|date = December 4, 2018|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref><ref name=npr-nakamoto/>
|-
| 2018 || || Detention statistics || Start || ICE || ICE begins publishing detainee deaths within 90 days of each death. This is because "Congressional requirements described in the Department of Homeland Security Appropriations Bill (2018) require ICE to make public all reports regarding an in-custody death within 90 days." The first reported death is for April 10, 2018.<ref name=ice-detainee-death-reporting>{{cite web|url = https://www.ice.gov/detain/detainee-death-reporting|title = Detainee Death Reporting|publisher = U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.congress.gov/congressional-report/115th-congress/house-report/239/1|title = H. Rept. 115-239 - DEPARTMENT OF HOMELAND SECURITY APPROPRIATIONS BILL, 2018|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref> Some immigrant justice and advocacy groups consider these reports to be shams that are more notifications of death than actual analyses of the cause of death.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://immigrantjustice.org/press-releases/ice-releases-sham-immigrant-death-reports-it-dodges-accountability-and-flouts|title = ICE Releases Sham Immigrant Death Reports As It Dodges Accountability And Flouts Congressional Requirements|date = December 19, 2018|publisher = National Immigrant Justice Center|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2019 || {{dts|January 29}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, DHS OIG || A report by the DHS Office of the Inspector General finds that "ICE does not adequately hold detention facility contractors accountable for not meeting performance standards." It makes five recommendations, all of which ICE accepts and proposes steps to implement.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.oig.dhs.gov/sites/default/files/assets/2019-02/OIG-19-18-Jan19.pdf|title = ICE Does Not Fully Use Contracting Tools to Hold Detention Facility Contractors Accountable for Failing to Meet Performance Standards|date = January 29, 2019|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = DHS Office of Inspector General}}</ref><ref name=npr-nakamoto/>
|-
| 2019 || {{dts|August 21}} || Detention standards (child detention) || Update || DHS, Department of Health and Human Services || DHS and the Department of Health and Human Services announce a final rule replacing the original ''Flores'' settlement rules, taking effect in 60 days. Importantly, this gets rid of the 20-day limit (introduced in 2015 by the Obama administration) on the duration that children can be detained.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dhs.gov/news/2019/08/21/dhs-and-hhs-announce-new-rule-implement-flores-settlement-agreement|title = DHS and HHS Announce New Rule to Implement the Flores Settlement Agreement; Final Rule Published to Fulfill Obligations under Flores Settlement Agreement|date = August 21, 2019|accessdate = October 13, 2021|publisher = U.S. Department of Homeland Security}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.dhs.gov/news/2019/08/21/acting-secretary-mcaleenan-dhs-hhs-federal-rule-flores-agreement|title = Acting Secretary of Homeland Security Kevin K. McAleenan on the DHS-HHS Federal Rule on Flores Agreement|date = August 21, 2019|accessdate = October 13, 2021|publisher = U.S. Department of Homeland Security}}</ref><ref name=nyt-flores-kill>{{cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/21/us/politics/flores-migrant-family-detention.html|title = Migrant Families Would Face Indefinite Detention Under New Trump Rule|date = August 21, 2019|accessdate = October 13, 2021|author = Michael D. Shear|author2 = Zolan Kanno-Youngs|publisher = New York Times}}</ref><ref name=tafsp/> The plan would be rejected by U.S. District Judge Dolly Gee of the Central District of California on September 5.<ref name=tafsp/>
|-
| 2019 || September || Detention standards (child detention) || Criticism/challenge || Department of Health and Human Services || A report by the Office of Inspector General (OIG) at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services looks into mental health challenges at child detention facilities run by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://oig.hhs.gov/oei/reports/oei-09-18-00431.pdf|title = Care Provider Facilities Described Challenges Addressing Mental Health Needs of Children in HHS Custody|author = Joanne M. Cheidi|date = September 1, 2019|accessdate = October 13, 2021|publisher = Office of Inspector General at U.S. Department of Health and Human Services}}</ref><ref name=tafsp/>
|-
| 2019 || {{dts|October}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, CBP, U.S. Commission on Civil Rights || The {{w|United States Commission on Civil Rights}} releases a report tittled "Trauma at the Border: The Human Cost of Inhumane Immigration Policies"; Chapter 3 of the report goes into detail on detention standards. The report recommends ending Zero Tolerance, ending family separation, and not detaining peope who have been passed the {{w|credible fear}} test.<ref name=usccr-2019>{{cite web|url = https://www.usccr.gov/pubs/2019/10-24-Trauma-at-the-Border.pdf|title = Trauma at the Border: The Human Cost of Inhumane Immigration Policies|date = October 1, 2019|accessdate = Julyl 27, 2021|publisher = United States Commission on Civil Rights}}</ref>
|-
| 2019 || || Detention standards || Start || ICE || ICE releases its 2019 National Detention Standards for Non-Dedicated Facilities. According to ICE: "These detention standards will apply to the approximately 45 U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement’s (ICE) Intergovernmental Service Agreement (IGSA) facilities currently operating under the NDS, approximately 35 United States Marshals Service (USMS) facilities used by ICE and which ICE inspects against the NDS, as well as approximately 60 facilities (both IGSA and USMS) which do not reach the threshold for ICE annual inspections – generally those with an Average Daily Population of less than 10."<ref name=nds-2019>{{cite web|url = https://www.ice.gov/detain/detention-management/2019|title = 2019 National Detention Standards for Non-Dedicated Facilities|publisher = U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2020 || || Detention standards || Start || ICE || ICE releases its 2020 Family Residential Standards.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.ice.gov/detain/detention-management/family-residential|title = Family Residential Standards 2020|publisher = U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|accessdate = April 29, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2020 || {{dts|March 24}} (publication), {{dts|April 21}} (public release) || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, CBP, GAO || A U.S. Government Accountability Office report looks at care of pregnant women in CBP's and ICE's detention facilities. It find an overall compliance rate of 79% or higher, and a minority of complaints about care of pregnant women to be substantiated, with many claims hard to adjudicate.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-20-330|title = Immigration Detention: Care of Pregnant Women in DHS Facilities|date = March 24, 2020|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref>
|-
| 2020 || {{dts|April 20}} onward || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE || Detainees at the Mesa Verde Detention Facility and the Yuba County Jail file a class action lawsuit against ICE in the {{w|United States District Court for the Northern District of California}}, alleging that conditions of confinement at these facilities violated their constitutional rights by exposing them to unreasonable risks of infection and death from COVID-19. Preliminary injunctions are issued in June 2020 and December 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aclunc.org/our-work/legal-docket/zepeda-rivas-v-jennings-immigration-detention|title = Zepeda Rivas v. Jennings (Immigration Detention)|publisher = ACLU Northern California|date = April 24, 2020|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.clearinghouse.net/detail.php?id=17534|title = Zepeda Rivas v. Jennings|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://cand.uscourts.gov/judges/chhabria-vince-vc/zepeda-rivas-et-al-v-jennings-et-al/|title = Zepeda Rivas, et al. v. Jennings, et al.|accessdate = July 4, 2021}}</ref> || California || Mesa Verde Detention Facility, Bakersfield; Yuba County Jail, Marysville, Yuba County
|-
| 2020 || {{dts|April 30}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || DHS/ICE || A report titled ''Justice-Free Zones: U.S. Immigration Detention under the Trump Administration'' is published jointly by the {{w|American Civil Liberties Union}}, Human Rights Watch, and National Immigrant Justice Center. The report describes the growth in immigration detention under the Trump administration, including the heavy reliance on private prisons to drive the growth in detention capacity, and the use of old prisons whose use was declining due to a reduction in incarceration. Detention conditions are described as "inhumane" and the term "black box" is used to describe people's challeges getting out of detention.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aclu.org/press-releases/new-report-shines-spotlight-abuses-and-growth-immigrant-detention-under-trump|title = New report shines spotlight on abuses and growth in immigrant detention under Trump|date = April 30, 2020|accessdate = October 13, 2021|publisher = American Civil Liberties Union}}</ref>
|-
| 2020 || {{dts|August 16}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, MVM Inc. || A report in the ''{{w|New York Times}}'' describes how MVM Inc., a transportation security company that ICE has contracted with in the past, has been extensively using hotel detention at ICE's request, to handle detention capacity that cannot be met at detention centers. While conditions in the hotels are reported to be generally better than detention centers, concerns are raised about the fact that legal protections for detainees do not contractually apply to hotel detention.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/08/16/us/migrant-children-hotels-coronavirus.html|title = A Private Security Company Is Detaining Migrant Children at Hotels. Under emergency coronavirus orders, the Trump administration is using hotels across the country to hold migrant children and families before expelling them.|last = Dickerson|first = Caitlin|date = August 16, 2020|accessdate = December 18, 2021}}</ref>
|-
| 2020 || {{dts|August 19}} || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GAO || A U.S. Government Accountability Office report concludes that ICE should enhance its use of facility oversight data and management of detainee complaints.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-20-596|title = Immigration Detention: ICE Should Enhance Its Use of Facility Oversight Data and Management of Detainee Complaints|date = August 19, 2020|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Government Accountability Office}}</ref>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|January 13}} (publication), February 13 (public release) || Detention standards || Criticism/challenge || ICE, GAO || A U.S. Government Accountability Office report suggests actions ICE should take to improve planning, documentation, and oversight of detention facility contracts.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.gao.gov/products/gao-21-149|title = Immigration Detention: Actions Needed to Improve Planning, Documentation, and Oversight of Detention Facility Contracts|date = January 13, 2021|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = U.S. Governmnt Accountability Office}}</ref><ref name=cbs-aclu-2021/>
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|March}} || Detention center (family detention) || ICE || ICE announces that all families that were being held at the Berks County detention center are no longer being held there, and that the detention center will no longer be used for family detention. There are plans to use it for adult detention in the future. The other two family detention centers, Dilley and Karnes, are to be used only for holding families for short, three-day periods.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.post-gazette.com/news/state/2021/03/03/Last-family-released-from-Berks-County-immigration-detention-center-pennsylvania/stories/202103030106|title = Last family released from Berks County immigration detention center|last = Hall|first = Peter|date = March 3, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = The Morning Call}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/us-says-it-will-stop-using-berks-co-detention-center-to-hold-migrant-families/2730911/|title = US Says It Will Stop Using Berks Co. Detention Center to Hold Migrant Families. The detention center in Pennsylvania will instead be used by ICE to hold adults, the government said|last = Merchant|first = Nomaan|date = March 6, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = NBC Philadelphia}}</ref> || Pennsylvania || Berks County Residential Center, Leesport, Berks County
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|March 20}} || Detention standards || || ICE, Endeavors || Axios reports that ICE awarded a $86 million contract to Endeavors, a Texas-based nonprofit, for hotel detention of migrants for the next six months in Arizona and Texas.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.axios.com/ice-hotel-rooms-border-migrant-families-7682092b-952c-428e-ae3b-f8b2d4072c0a.html|title = Scoop: ICE securing hotel rooms to hold growing number of migrant families|date = March 20, 2021|accessdate = December 18, 2021|publisher = Axios}}</ref> || Arizona, Texas
|-
| 2021 || {{dts|April 28}} || Detention center || Criticism/challenge || ICE || The {{w|American Civil Liberties Union}} calls on DHS/ICE to shut down 39 ICE detention facilities, citing historically low occupancy rates and the costs of maintaining unused detention space.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.aclu.org/press-releases/aclu-calls-biden-administration-shut-down-ice-detention-facilities|title = ACLU calls on Biden administration to shut down ice detention facilities. Low detention numbers pose unique opportunity to shut down architecture used to abuse and traumatize immigrants|date = April 28, 2021|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = American Civil Liberties Union}}</ref><ref name=cbs-aclu-2021>{{cite web|url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/immigration-aclu-biden-administration-close-ice-detention-facilities/|title = ACLU calls on Biden administration to close dozens of ICE detention facilities|last = Sganga|first = Nicole|last2 = Montoya-Galvez|first2 = Camilo|date = April 28, 2021|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = CBS News}}</ref> In response, ICE says that the current low occupancy is due to having released detaines to comply with {{w|social distancing}} requirements during the {{w|COVID-19 pandemic}}, and future occupancy may be higher. ICE also explains that by making guaranteed payments even for unused beds, it is able to negotiate lower overall rates.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.npr.org/2021/04/28/991679868/aclu-calls-on-dhs-to-close-ice-detention-centers-citing-high-cost-of-empty-beds|title = ACLU Calls On DHS To Close ICE Detention Centers, Citing High Cost Of Empty Beds|last = Rose|first = Joel|date = April 28, 2021|accessdate = July 4, 2021|publisher = NPR}}</ref>
